  "text": "The PromQL query parsing and validation pipeline in prometheus/prometheus consists of the following key components:\n\n## Parser Interface and Implementation (promql/parser/parse.go)\nThe Parser interface (line 51-59) defines the public parsing API with methods including ParseExpr(input string) (Expr, error). The promQLParser struct (line 61-63) implements this interface. The concrete parser struct (line 143-167) is the low-level parser that orchestrates parsing with the lexer and yacc-generated parser. Key methods include ParseExpr (line 70-74) which delegates to parseExpr (line 196+), and checkAST (line 719-731+) which validates AST nodes for type correctness during parsing.\n\n## AST Node Type Definitions (promql/parser/ast.go)\nThe Expr interface (line 76-85) is the core abstraction for all expression types. Expression node types are implemented as concrete structs:\n- AggregateExpr (line 91-98): Aggregation operations (sum, avg, max, etc.)\n- BinaryExpr (line 100-111): Binary operations between two expressions\n- Call (line 123-129): Function call expressions\n- DurationExpr (line 113-121): Duration arithmetic expressions\n- MatrixSelector (line 131-139): Range vector selections with time ranges\n- SubqueryExpr (line 141-160): Subquery expressions\n- NumberLiteral (line 162-168): Numeric constants\n- ParenExpr (line 170-175): Parenthesized expressions\n- StringLiteral (line 177-181): String constants\n- UnaryExpr (line 183-190): Unary operations\n- VectorSelector (line 205-235): Instant vector selections with label matchers, supporting Anchored and Smoothed modifiers\n- StepInvariantExpr (line 192-197): Step-invariant expressions used for optimization\nEach expression type implements a Type() method that returns ValueType for type validation.\n\n## Lexer and Tokenizer (promql/parser/lex.go)\nThe Lexer struct (line 275-278) maintains the scanner state for the input string. It produces Item tokens (line 25-30) with ItemType classification. ItemType values represent different token categories including operators (arithmetic and comparison), aggregators, keywords, and identifiers. The lexer implements various state functions for tokenizing different syntactic elements.\n\n## Generated yacc Parser (promql/parser/generated_parser.y and generated_parser.y.go)\nThe yacc grammar file (generated_parser.y) defines the PromQL grammar rules for parsing expressions. It is compiled into generated_parser.y.go by goyacc. The generated parser produces AST nodes from the token stream produced by the Lexer. Binary expressions use the newBinaryExpression method to construct BinaryExpr nodes.\n\n## Function Registry (promql/parser/functions.go)\nThe Function struct (line 16-24) represents a PromQL function with Name, ArgTypes (parameter types), ReturnType, Variadic properties, and Experimental flag. The Functions map (line 26-27+) is the global registry of all PromQL functions including abs, absent, absent_over_time, acos, acosh, asin, asinh, atan, atanh, avg_over_time, ceil, changes, clamp, clamp_max, clamp_min, and many others. The getFunction helper (line 470-474) retrieves functions by name from this registry.\n\n## Value Type System (promql/parser/value.go)\nThe ValueType type (line 22-23) represents the result type of expressions. Four main types are defined: ValueTypeVector (instant vector), ValueTypeMatrix (range vector), ValueTypeScalar (numeric value), and ValueTypeString (string value). The DocumentedType function provides user-facing terminology. This type system is used throughout type checking in checkAST.\n\n## Engine Integration (promql/engine.go)\nThe Engine struct (line 345-361) integrates the parser into the query execution pipeline. It holds a parser.Parser instance (line 340). EngineOpts (line 281-341) configures the engine including parser options. NewEngine (line 363-450+) creates a new Engine instance, initializing the parser via NewParser if not provided. The Engine processes parsed AST from the parser through its query execution path.\n\n## Functions Implementation (promql/functions.go)\nThe FunctionCall type (line 39-60) defines the signature for function implementations that process evaluated arguments. The FunctionCalls map (line 2151-2154+) contains the runtime implementations of PromQL functions. There are also special function registries like AnchoredSafeFunctions (line 2254-2259) and SmoothedSafeFunctions (line 2265-2270) that define which functions support these modifiers.\n\n## Features Registration (promql/parser/features.go)\nThe RegisterFeatures method (line 21-58) registers PromQL language features with the feature registry, including keywords (like 'anchored' and 'smoothed' for extended range selectors), operators, aggregators, and functions. This enables feature flags for experimental features controlled by EnableExperimentalFunctions option.\n\n## Supporting Components\n- promql/parser/printer.go: Provides Tree() and other printing utilities for AST nodes\n- promql/parser/prettier.go: Handles formatting and pretty-printing of AST nodes\n- promql/value.go: Defines the Value interface for query result values\n\n## Pipeline Flow\nThe parsing and validation pipeline flows as follows: NewParser creates a promQLParser -> ParseExpr calls parseExpr on a new low-level parser -> parseExpr calls parseGenerated which uses the lexer to tokenize and the yacc parser to parse -> checkAST recursively validates the resulting AST for type correctness -> the validated AST is returned to the caller and eventually passed to Engine for execution."
